  "local_port": 49114,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some ideas for projects in data structures using C/C++?",
  "response": "Here are some project ideas using data structures in C/C++ that can help improve your skills and understanding of the subject:\n\n### 1. **Text Editor**\n   - Implement a simple text editor with features like insert, delete, and search. Use data structures like lists and stacks to manage the command history (undo/redo functionality).\n\n### 2. **Library Management System**\n   - Create a system to manage a library's book inventory. Implement a class for books and use trees or hash tables to allow quick searching based on titles, authors, or genres.\n\n### 3. **Social Network Graph**\n   - Build a basic social network model where users can add friends, remove friends, and discover mutual friends. Use a graph data structure to represent users and their friendships.\n\n### 4. **Maze Solver**\n   - Represent a maze using a 2D array and implement algorithms like depth-first search (DFS) or breadth-first search (BFS) to solve it. Visualize the path found through the maze.\n\n### 5. **Binary Search Tree Visualizer**\n   - Create a program that allows users to insert, delete, and search for nodes in a binary search tree. Additionally, visualize the tree structure using ASCII art or a graphical library.\n\n### 6. **Priority Queue Implementation**\n   - Implement a priority queue using different data structures (e.g., arrays and heaps). Compare their performance based on different operations, and demonstrate usage in scenarios like task scheduling.\n\n### 7. **Dictionary/Spell Checker**\n   - Create a spell checker that uses a trie or hash table to store valid words. Implement features to suggest corrections based on the entered word.\n\n### 8. **Graph Algorithms**\n   - Implement various graph algorithms (Dijkstra, Kruskal, Prim) and visualize their workings. Allow users to input a graph and interactively see the algorithm's steps.\n\n### 9. **Cache Simulator**\n   - Build a cache simulator to illustrate how different cache algorithms (LRU, FIFO) work. Use data structures like doubly linked lists and hash maps to implement the caching.\n\n### 10. **Web Crawler**\n   - Implement a basic web crawler that collects data from websites and stores it in a suitable data structure. Use a hash table to record visited URLs and a queue for exploring new links.\n\n### 11. **Game Development: Tic Tac Toe**\n   - Create a console-based Tic Tac Toe game using arrays or an appropriate data structure to manage the game state. Include features like checking for winning conditions and displaying the board.\n\n### 12. **Job Scheduling Simulator**\n   - Implement a job scheduling simulator that uses queues to manage different jobs. Allow you to compare various scheduling algorithms (FCFS, SJF, Round Robin) and their effects on job wait times.\n\n### 13. **Compiler Construction: Expression Parser**\n   - Create a simple expression parser using stacks to evaluate mathematical expressions (infix, postfix, prefix). Implement operator precedence and handle errors gracefully.\n\n### 14. **Stock Price Tracker**\n   - Build a stock price tracker that allows users to input stock prices over time. Use linked lists to store data and implement functionalities to find the highest, lowest, and average prices.\n\n### 15. **URL Shortener**\n   - Develop a URL shortener using hash tables to map long URLs to short codes. Keep track of visit counts for each short URL.\n\n### Bonus: **Data Structures Library**\n   - Create your own library of data structures (linked lists, trees, graphs, hash tables) with standard operations (insert, delete, search), and make it available for reuse in other projects.\n\nThese projects will not only help you learn data structures but also improve your coding skills in C/C++. Make sure to document your code and highlight the rationale for your design choices!",
